WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.960
 So it's pretty easy to get confused when you're first looking at data models,

00:00:03.960 --> 00:00:06.600
 migrations, and the database itself.

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:10.560
 And so I wanna go through this in a little bit more detail.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:16.720
 So the makeMigrations is what reads the models.py files and

00:00:16.720 --> 00:00:19.200
 then it creates what are called migrations.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:24.520
 And the key thing is this is guided by the list of applications and settings.py.

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:28.080
 So if you make a new thing and make a new application, and

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:31.200
 you edit the model stuff file, and you try to run and make migrations and

00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:33.800
 it doesn't see anything, you're like, what did it just do?

00:00:33.800 --> 00:00:35.720
 Well, did you edit your settings.py?

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:38.760
 Cuz there is a thing called installed apps in your settings.py.

00:00:38.760 --> 00:00:43.040
 Now migrations are portable across databases.

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:48.080
 This means that the migration is a logical description of what the tables

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:51.400
 should look like, and they're an evolution.

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:55.520
 What they mean is like the first version of this table from the first models.py

00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:58.200
 when migrations was first run is 001.

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:02.020
 And then if you change models.py and you run a migration again,

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:08.000
 it looks at the changes from the migration 001 to models.py and then 002.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.960
 And then 002 is not like wipe it all out and start over.

00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:14.400
 It's like, wait, you just added one column.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:16.200
 I'll go ahead and add that column.

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:18.880
 But it's not done it in a way that's actual SQL.

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:23.240
 So migrations are themselves kind of Python like, and

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:27.400
 they're portable across databases, which means that you might, on your computer,

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:31.120
 use SQLite, and in production you might use MySQL.

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:34.240
 And the migrations are the same for both of them, cuz they're just saying,

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:37.320
 here's the columns, here's the types, here's what they're supposed to be.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:42.000
 Now, contrast that with a migrate command.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.640
 The migrate command reads all the migrations and then knows what database

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:52.160
 it's talking to and runs the SQL commands to create the necessary tables and or

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:53.440
 evolve the necessary tables.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:56.800
 So it looks and says, here's the first migration, here's the second migration,

00:01:56.800 --> 00:01:58.160
 here's the third migration.

00:01:58.160 --> 00:02:01.040
 I'll make the table, I'll change the table, I'll change the table,

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:01.800
 I'll change the table.

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:05.320
 And at the end of all the migration, the migrate then goes through all

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:10.280
 the migrations and then has a database table that reflects the sum total

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:16.600
 of the migrations, which also reflects the latest models.py file.

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:21.000
 So it's a little complex, it has to do with database portability and

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.200
 the fact that we wanna separate out the portable parts of this from

00:02:25.200 --> 00:02:27.360
 the non-portable parts to this.

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:32.120
 So if you look at the make migrations, and here's in dj4e-samples,

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:34.960
 my little sample stuff, there's lots of models in there.

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:37.880
 And if you take a look at all the models.py, you see that for

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:43.720
 every application in the dj4e-samples project, you see a models.py file.

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:49.000
 And that's a Python code, that's class, book, blah, blah, blah.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.920
 That's very portable and that's how we, in our Python code,

00:02:52.920 --> 00:02:56.520
 in our Django code, see the database model.

00:02:56.520 --> 00:03:00.680
 And when you run the make migration, that produces these migrations files.

00:03:00.680 --> 00:03:05.440
 And they're just in like autos, migrations, 001 initial.py, etc.

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:10.020
 And so you see some of the ones I have here, there's actually two of them.

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:14.760
 So it sort of made the first one, and then I must have changed the models file.

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:19.740
 And then I ran make migrations again, and it showed, it recorded how that model

00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:23.160
 changed from the first version of the models file to the second version.

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:28.200
 You can look at these, don't edit them, you can check them into GitHub,

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:29.360
 but don't edit these.

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:33.240
 But take a look, they're a very portable representation,

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:35.920
 they kinda look like the models.py file.

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:36.960
 You're not supposed to change them,

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:40.600
 you're supposed to generate them with make migrations.

00:03:40.600 --> 00:03:42.800
 And again, those can go into GitHub.

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:47.960
 Now, the migrate basically reads all those migration files.

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:51.480
 And not just one, but if there's a sequence of migration files,

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:54.280
 it applies them all in order as needed.

00:03:54.280 --> 00:03:58.000
 And if the database has the first and second migration applied, but

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.880
 not the third one, it knows that and says, you know what?

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.720
 I'm gonna just tweak this database that already exists, it's already running, and

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:07.160
 then add a column, or change the width of a column, or

00:04:07.160 --> 00:04:11.320
 whatever it is that you've asked to be done by editing your models.py.

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:14.040
 So when the migrate is done,

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:17.560
 you then end up with a whole bunch of tables in your database.

00:04:17.560 --> 00:04:20.400
 And they're all based on the name of the application, and

00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:23.680
 the name of the model within the application.

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:30.440
 And so somewhere in here is Book One Book, Book One Instance, and Book One Lang.

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:33.160
 They're all sitting there, and so those are all the tables.

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:36.640
 And we took a look at those tables before, but that's the migrate.

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:41.000
 That goes from all the little migrations spread across all the applications in

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:46.120
 this project, and then puts a database together that has all those things.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:49.960
 And I keep saying that the migrations are all about evolution, right?

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:56.840
 Cuz if you take a look here, you see one little table called Django Migrations.

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:00.480
 And what Django's doing in that Django Migrations table is remembering

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:03.520
 which of those migrations have already been applied to this database.

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:07.240
 So as it's going through the migrations, it says, here's one that's not yet

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:10.320
 done in this database, so I gotta tweak the database just a little bit.

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:13.040
 So it remembers the migrations that have been done.

00:05:13.040 --> 00:05:19.040
 It's pretty fascinating, and in these little tiny applications,

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:22.400
 we don't always need to be so clever about that.

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:27.360
 So sometimes what you wanna do is just like, hmm, I'm confused.

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:30.160
 I'm gonna rerun the make migrate, cuz you're not really running production,

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:32.080
 you're just really doing it over and over again.

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:34.880
 So you can rerun the make migrate.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:38.240
 And the way you do this is you basically simply delete the file.

00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:40.520
 You can delete these files.

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:43.380
 I would delete all the ones that start with zero, right?

00:05:43.380 --> 00:05:48.200
 If you're gonna rerun make migrate, just rerun make migrations,

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:54.560
 delete all the ones that start with zero, and this is an application, migrations,

00:05:54.560 --> 00:05:56.280
 and then get rid of all these.

00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:59.520
 And then you can rerun the make migrations, and

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:05.720
 it will read your models.py file, and then it will do all of the necessary things

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:09.280
 to recreate the migration file, right?

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:10.520
 Now that's not the database.

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:13.840
 That is the instructions on how to create the database, okay?

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:15.320
 So that's how you rerun make migrate.

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:17.920
 You can run migrate from scratch.

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:19.360
 This is actually easier.

00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:23.680
 So you can kind of wipe out the migrations for one application, and

00:06:23.680 --> 00:06:26.720
 I did that, just wiped out the book one here.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:28.480
 That's what I did and started over.

00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:33.600
 But you can wipe out all the migrations and all the database and

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:37.880
 everything by just removing the file, in this case, cuz we're running SQLite.

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:41.680
 Just wipe out the file rmdb.sqlite, cuz after migrate,

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:44.400
 that's where everything ends up, is in that file.

00:06:44.400 --> 00:06:46.280
 So then you wipe that out, it's gone.

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:49.120
 Now you might have created an administrator account or something, and

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:50.040
 you're gonna wipe that out too.

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:53.720
 You're gonna wipe the data out, you're gonna wipe the tables out, it's all gone.

00:06:53.720 --> 00:06:54.960
 That's one thing I like about SQLite.

00:06:54.960 --> 00:06:58.160
 You remove this one file, and it's literally all gone.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:02.920
 And then you rerun python manage3 migrate, and it reads all the migrations and

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:06.200
 makes you a nice, clean, perfect, empty database.

00:07:06.200 --> 00:07:09.960
 So if you're kinda stuck, and you're not afraid of losing your data,

00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:12.120
 which in most of the beginning programmers,

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:15.840
 it's okay to wipe out your SQLite thing and run migrate again.

00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:17.560
 Just go ahead and try it.

00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:21.680
 Like I said, if you made an admin account, well, you gotta make it again.

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:22.840
 But that's the worst that you can do.

00:07:22.840 --> 00:07:25.960
 So at least in these beginning applications.

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:30.400
 So now that we've talked about how to come up with a data model,

00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:34.800
 how to encode it in Django model.py, how to do migrations, and

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:37.520
 how to migrate stuff, and how to make a database out of it.

00:07:37.520 --> 00:07:41.120
 Now we're gonna talk about the kind of Python code that you can run

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:43.440
 to update these models in the database.

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:53.440
 [MUSIC]

